# Theory

The core policy theory is that the Fed can move one tool, the policy interest rate, to influence both sides of its mandate over time:

- Higher interest rates reduce borrowing, spending, and pricing pressure, helping inflation move down.
- Lower interest rates support borrowing and demand, helping employment recover when labor markets weaken.

In practice, this is not instant. Inflation and unemployment usually respond with lags, and shocks can temporarily break the tradeoff.

